---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Finishing" description="Deploy, hosting, custom domains, and reflection.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Finishing</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">The final ticket deploys the site. Then: hosting options, optional custom domain, and reflection.</p>

  <!-- Ticket 8 -->
  <h2 class="mb-4">Ticket 8: Deploy</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-2">Tell Claude:</p>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Start Ticket 8: Deploy.

Deploy the site to Netlify free tier. Verify all sections load correctly on the live URL.`}</CodeBlock>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mt-4 mb-3"><strong>Your verification focus:</strong></p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-4">
    <li>Open the live URL on your phone — does everything load?</li>
    <li>Tap the phone number — does it open the dialer?</li>
    <li>Check images aren't broken</li>
    <li>Run Lighthouse on the live URL (not localhost) — performance 80+, SEO 90+</li>
  </ul>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Troubleshooting: "The deploy failed"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Read the error message. Copy it. Paste to Claude: "The deploy failed with this error: [paste]. Fix it." You don't fix it — you communicate the error and direct the fix. This is directing.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Hosting -->
  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Hosting & Custom Domains</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Netlify, Vercel, Cloudflare Pages, and GitHub Pages are all <strong class="text-text">static hosting providers</strong>. They serve pre-built files — no server running your code, no database to maintain. That's why they can offer free tiers: serving static files is cheap. For a site like GreenScape, free hosting is the right choice — exactly what Ken asked for.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The free URL works fine for development and learning. But if you were handing this to Ken as a real client, you'd want a custom domain — <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">greenscapelandscaping.com.au</code> instead of a <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">netlify.app</code> subdomain.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Optional: buy a custom domain</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This is entirely optional but worth the experience if you want to see the full delivery flow. A domain costs $1–15/year depending on the extension (.com, .com.au, .dev). You can buy one from:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-4">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Cloudflare</strong> — sells domains at cost (no markup), also offers free DNS and CDN</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Namecheap</strong> — often has cheap first-year deals</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Google Domains</strong> (now Squarespace) — straightforward</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Once you own a domain, you point it at your hosting provider (Netlify, Cloudflare Pages, etc.) by updating the DNS records. Every provider has a guide for this. The whole process takes about 15 minutes plus up to an hour for DNS to propagate.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Buying a domain for $5, linking it to a site you built, and sending someone the URL — that's a different feeling from <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">something.netlify.app</code>. If you're building a portfolio or want to experience what it's like to deliver a site to a client, it's worth doing once.</p>

  <!-- Reflect -->
  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Reflect</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Before moving to Project 2, ask yourself:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>Did Claude add anything not in the PRD? Did I catch it?</li>
    <li>Did the design match what I expected? Did I catch any discrepancies?</li>
    <li>How did the first deploy go? Did something go wrong?</li>
    <li>What was confusing? What felt natural?</li>
    <li>Could I do this again without the guide?</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- Show someone -->
  <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6 my-8 bg-bg-subtle text-center">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Show someone</h3>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-3">Open the live URL on your phone. Show it to a friend, a classmate, or a family member.</p>
    <p class="text-text-secondary font-medium">"I directed AI to build this."</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-3">That feeling is the point of Project 1.</p>
  </div>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>What you've learned:</strong> Set up a project, direct Claude through 8 tickets, verify against a design spec with DevTools, catch anti-scope violations, read AI reviews, deploy to a live URL, and handle failures by communicating errors. The loop is yours now.</p>
  </Callout>
</DocsLayout>
